<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="448" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,645]" pageId="5" pageNumber="448">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,367,392]" pageId="5" pageNumber="448">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name, 
<taxonomicName box="[476,604,368,392]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Podalonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="448" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicellularis">
<emphasis box="[476,604,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="448">bicellularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, derived from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[894,916,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="448">bi</emphasis>
- (= two), and Latin 
<emphasis box="[1161,1267,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="448">cellularis</emphasis>
(= wing cell), refers to the forewing with two submarginal cells, which is one recognition characters of this species. It is a feminine adjective.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="448" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,645]" pageId="5" pageNumber="448">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,297,476,501]" pageId="5" pageNumber="448">Remark</emphasis>
. Most species of this genus from 
<collectingCountry box="[707,774,476,501]" name="China" pageId="5" pageNumber="448">China</collectingCountry>
have three submarginal cells in the forewing. This new species is remarkable in having only two submarginal cells. However, this may not be a constant feature, because variation in the number of submarginal cells has been observed in 
<taxonomicName box="[895,1106,548,572]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Podalonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="448" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parvula">
